{
  "schema_version": "1.0",
  "id": "lawn_driving",
  "kind": "curve",
  "meta": {
    "title": "Driving after a First-Ever Seizure — recurrence & COSY by aetiology",
    "doi": "10.1136/jnnp-2024-333684",
    "pmid": "38925913",
    "authors": "Lawn N, Lee J, Dunne J",
    "year": 2025,
    "journal": "J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry",
    "outcome": "Cumulative seizure-recurrence risk and the annual chance of a seizure (COSY) after a first-ever seizure, by aetiology — to inform private and commercial driving eligibility",
    "cff_info": "<p><b>What this shows.</b> Seizure-recurrence risk after a <b>first-ever seizure</b> and the resulting driving eligibility, from a large prospective cohort (n=1714; Lawn et&nbsp;al., <i>JNNP</i> 2025). Pick the aetiological group to see its cumulative recurrence curve and its <b>COSY</b> (chance of a seizure in the next year) with time seizure-free.</p><h4>Key findings — driving</h4><ul><li>Private driving (annual risk ≤20%) is usually allowed after ~6 months seizure-free; the annual risk drops below 20% early for all groups.</li><li>Commercial driving needs the annual risk (COSY) below <b>2%</b>. For an <b>unprovoked</b> first seizure this is not reached until <b>~9 years</b> seizure-free — even with a normal EEG and MRI (5-yr annual risk still ~3.9%).</li><li>For an <b>acute symptomatic</b> first seizure the annual risk falls below 2% after ~4 years.</li><li>Highest recurrence: unprovoked remote-symptomatic (~75% at 10 yr); lowest: acute symptomatic–systemic (~38%).</li></ul><p>The COSY curve and the 20% / 2% driving-orientation marks are derived directly from the recurrence data. Local licensing laws vary — this is a demonstration tool, not a licensing decision.</p>"
  },
  "thresholds": {
    "group1": 20,
    "group2": 2
  },
